{# ══ Review ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}
<p>Expand each concept to check your understanding before moving on.</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u05-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-u05-a", "Conditional statement — what are the key parts?") %}
  <p>A conditional has two parts: the <strong>antecedent</strong> (P — the "if" part, the condition) and the <strong>consequent</strong> (Q — the "then" part, the result). The conditional is false only when P is true and Q is false. In all other cases it is true.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u05-b", "Contrapositive — why is it special?") %}
  <p>The contrapositive (<em>If not Q, then not P</em>) is logically equivalent to the original conditional — they always have the same truth value. The converse and inverse are equivalent to each other but not to the original. Confusing the original with its converse is the source of the fallacy of affirming the consequent.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u05-c", "Five valid propositional forms — what are they?") %}
  <p>
    <strong>1. Modus Ponens (MP)</strong>: If P then Q; P; therefore Q.<br>
    <strong>2. Modus Tollens (MT)</strong>: If P then Q; not Q; therefore not P.<br>
    <strong>3. Hypothetical Syllogism (HS)</strong>: If P then Q; if Q then R; therefore if P then R.<br>
    <strong>4. Disjunctive Syllogism (DS)</strong>: P or Q; not P; therefore Q.<br>
    <strong>5. Constructive Dilemma (CD)</strong>: P or Q; if P then R; if Q then S; therefore R or S.
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u05-d", "Two invalid forms to avoid — how do you spot them?") %}
  <p><strong>Affirming the consequent</strong>: If P then Q; Q; therefore P — invalid because Q can be true for reasons other than P. <strong>Denying the antecedent</strong>: If P then Q; not P; therefore not Q — invalid for the same reason. Both sound plausible but fail because they confuse sufficiency with necessity.</p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

